{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3c1b88de-c0a9-4eaf-9e45-fd5eca1d2348","content":"Use `dotnet watch test` — it re-runs tests automatically whenever you save a file. To focus on just your failing test:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch test --filter \"RemoveStock_ExceedsAvailable_ThrowsException\"\n```\n\n**The bug:** `RemoveStock` subtracts without checking availability. It should throw when `quantity > available`. Fix line 36-37:\n\n```csharp\npublic void RemoveStock(string sku, int quantity)\n{\n    var current = _stock.GetValueOrDefault(sku);\n    if (quantity > current)\n        throw new InvalidOperationException($\"Cannot remove {quantity}; only {current} in stock.\");\n    _stock[sku] = current - quantity;\n}\n```\n\nOnce `dotnet watch` is running, just save the file and it will automatically re-run the test so you can verify the fix.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2128171e-07ba-4c1e-bd88-f83e12fd4319","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to set up hot reload for their test project. With .NET and Microsoft.Testing.Platform (as configured in global.json), they can use `dotnet test --hotreload` or `dotnet watch test` to get hot reload for tests.\n\nActually, looking at the setup more carefully:\n- .NET 10 with Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner\n- MSTest 3.8.0\n\nFor .NET testing with hot reload, `dotnet watch test` is the standard approach. But with the Microsoft.Testing.Platform, there might be a more specific approach.\n\nActually, with modern .NET (especially .NET 10), `dotnet test --hotreload` might be available, or `dotnet watch test` is the classic way.\n\n\nI'll recommend `dotnet watch test` as the simplest way to re-run tests whenever files change, and they can narrow it down to a specific test using the `--filter` flag with the test name.","outputTokens":467,"requestId":"E3CA:9C8D1:6ADDF1:7ADD9D:6A052920"},"id":"2aacd242-dc44-47bc-98e6-e1b196567bb0","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:45:15.323Z","parentId":"3627bb4f-1676-4617-b6b4-5